t allow other constituents to appear in the sentence initial position. One of these constructions is ay-inversion. Although it is often labeled a topic-marking construction, it is actually far more versatile. This book aims to explore some of its many facets. The investigation of ay-inversion begins with a survey of its various uses that appear in the data, including some that have to date received very little if any attention in the literature, such as reversed ang-inversion, which combines two of the language’s inversion constructions. Selected observations are then modeled in Role and Reference Grammar and their implications for Tagalog syntax are explored. Finally, the role of ay-inversion in anaphora resolution is investigated and selected processes are modeled in a frame-based account.  afunded by Heinrich-Heine-Universität Düsseldorf  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 4aAustronesische Sprachen. 4aMorphosyntax. 4aTagalog. 4aVan Valin, Robert D. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAustronesian Languages.  aInformation Structure.  aMorphosyntax.  aTagalog.2 aHeinrich-Heine-Universität Düsseldorfefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd0 cEPUBz97831107555580 cprintz978311075498840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311075546640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110755466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110755466/original  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK